Rain forecast

Shipeng Wang

August 16, 2019

Introduction

Topic

The main topic is the weather indicator given by the weather station in Australia. I am very interested in this. Since ancient times, we hope to make a prediction about the weather. In the past, we predicted whether it would rain on the second day by observing the color of the twilight weather and the thickness of the clouds. Now we are able to quantify the weather so we can make predictions more accurately.

Dataset

Observations were drawn from numerous weather stations. The daily observations are available from http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/data. Copyright Commonwealth of Australia 2010, Bureau of Meteorology.

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/jsphyg/weather-dataset-rattle-package

Goal

The main goal is to answer whether it will rain the next day, or what the probability of rain. By analyzing the weather indicators of the day, we need to find data related to whether it rains or not, and then build appropriate models among them to predict the weather of the next day.

Variable

Variable Type Unit Meaning
Date Continuous Day The date of observation
MinTemp Continuous Degrees celsius The minimum temperature in degrees celsius
MaxTemp Continuous Degrees celsius The maximum temperature in degrees celsius
Rainfall Continuous mm The amount of rainfall recorded for the day in mm
Evaporation Continuous mm The so-called Class A pan evaporation (mm) in the 24 hours to 9am
Sunshine Continuous Hour The number of hours of bright sunshine in the day
WindGustSpeed Continuous km/h The speed (km/h) of the strongest wind gust in the 24 hours to midnight
WindSpeed9am Continuous km/hr Wind speed (km/hr) averaged over 10 minutes prior to 9am
WindSpeed3pm Continuous km/hr Wind speed (km/hr) averaged over 10 minutes prior to 3pm
Humidity9am Continuous Percent Humidity (percent) at 9am
Humidity3pm Continuous Percent Humidity (percent) at 3pm
Pressure9am Continuous hpa Atmospheric pressure (hpa) reduced to mean sea level at 9am
Pressure3pm Continuous hpa Atmospheric pressure (hpa) reduced to mean sea level at 3pm
Cloud9am Continuous oktas Fraction of sky obscured by cloud at 9am
Cloud3pm Continuous oktas Fraction of sky obscured by cloud at 9am
Temp9am Continuous Degrees celsius Temperature (degrees C) at 9am

Feature engineering

The first step is to think about which columns to keep as the predictive variables that we put into the model. I decide to use MinTemp,MaxTemp,Humidity9am,Humidity3pm,Pressure9am" and Pressure3pm as predictor variables, and RainTomorrow as target variable.

If it rains the next day, the clouds will accumulate in advance, and the temperature and air pressure will decrease significantly as the clouds thicken, so I used temperature and pressure as my predictor variables. The reason I choose humidity is when the clouds accumulate, because the sunshine is reduced, so the humidity in the air will increase appropriately, so I think the humidity can also help us to predict whether it will rain the next day.

So I need to put my chosen variables into the new data set.

data <- data[,c(3,4,14,15,16,17,24)]

  replace_na(median(data$MaxTemp, na.rm=TRUE))

We can see from the result that PC1 can explain 69.32% of variance and PC2 can explain 15.60%. The cumulative proportion of PC3 is 94.70% of variance, so we can use 3 principle components for this analysis.

In addition, I also made scree plot to help us choose the number of PC better.

plot(pca,
     type="line",
     main="Scree Plot")
abline(h=1,col="blue")

In Scree plot, we can find that after the two PCs, the steps tend to be the same, so for this analysis, we can use two or three PCs for dimension reduction.

Here I try out three PCS for analysis.

PC_df <- pca$x[,1:3]
PC_df <- as.data.frame(PC_df)
PC_df <- cbind(RainTomorrow = data$RainTomorrow, PC_df)

Modeling

3 PCs

I choose to use logistic regression to predict the probability of RainTomorrow. First, I divided the data set into two parts. 80% of the data were randomly divided into train sets, while the remaining 20% of the data were test sets.

set.seed(1) 
row.number <- sample(x=1:nrow(PC_df), size=0.8*nrow(PC_df))
train = PC_df[row.number,]
test = PC_df[-row.number,]

Then I built the logistic regression model and trained it with the train set. The results are as follows.

logistic_model <- glm(RainTomorrow ~ PC1+PC2+PC3, family=binomial(link="logit"), data=train)
summary(logistic_model)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = RainTomorrow ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3, family = binomial(link = "logit"),

From the result we can see:

1: All the P-values of three components are small, so all the components have a significant correlation with the target variable.

2: For each additional unit of PC1, the log odds of rain will decrease by 0.11.

3: For each additional unit of PC2, the log odds of rain will decrease by 1.11.

4: For each additional unit of PC3, the log odds of rain will incresed by 0.19.

In the result we can see the models prediction of the probability of rain. If it is greater than 0.5, then I set it to 1, and the other data is set to 0.

pred <- predict(logistic_model, newdata = test, type = "response")

y_pred_num <- ifelse(pred > 0.5, 1, 0)
y_predicted <- factor(y_pred_num, levels=c(0, 1))
y_observed <- test$RainTomorrow

For this part I put the Confusion matrix to help me calculate the accuracy of this model.

ct_3PCs = table (y_predicted, y_observed)
ct_3PCs
##            y_observed
## y_predicted     0     1
##           0 20913  3851
##           1  1136  2539

And then I calculate the Precision, Recall and F1 Score of this 3PCs model.

Precision_3PC = 20926 / (20926+3932)
Recall_3PC = 20926 / (20926+1123)
F1_Score_3PC = 2*Precision_3PC*Recall_3PC/(Precision_3PC+Recall_3PC)
Precision_3PC
## [1] 0.8418215
Recall_3PC
## [1] 0.949068
F1_Score_3PC
## [1] 0.8922336

As we can see, the Precision is 0.84, which means that if the model predicts that it will not rain the next day, the accuracy rate will reach 84.18%.

The Recall is 0.94, which means that if it will not rain the next day, the probability that the model give the correct predictive is 94.90%.

F1 Score is Harmonic mean, this is kind of an average when x and y are equal. But when x and y are different, then its closer to the smaller number as compared to the larger number. It makes more sense for us to measure the accuracy of the model. As we can see, the F1 Score is 0.89, it is a really high score, which means that the model that have 3 PCs can explain 89.22% of the data.

Comparison

Num_PC=c("3_PCs","3_PCs","3_PCs","2_PCs","2_PCs","2_PCs","0_PCs","0_PCs","0_PCs")
Type=c("Precision","Recal","F1_Score","Precision","Recal","F1_Score","Precision","Recal","F1_Score")
Percents=c(Precision_3PC,Recall_3PC,F1_Score_3PC,Precision_2PC,Recall_2PC,F1_Score_2PC,Precision_0PC,Recall_0PC,F1_Score_0PC)
df=data.frame(Num_PC,Type,Percents)
ggplot(df, aes(x=factor(Type), y=Percents, colour=Num_PC,group=Num_PC)) + geom_line() +geom_point() + labs(title="Comparison")

By comparison, we can see that after PCA, we can greatly improve the accuracy of the model. We can see that in the performance of the three values, 0_PC is much lower than 2_PCs and 3_PCs. And in the comparison of 2_PCs and 3_PCs, we can find that there is almost no difference in the correct rate. In addition, we can find that the model performs best on Recal, the highest value is close to 0.95, and there is room for improvement in Precision. However, from the final F1_Score point of view, 2_PCs and 3_PCs can approach 0.90. I am satisfied with this result because it is at a higher level.

Conclusions

1: In the case of temperature, humidity and air pressure, the establishment of PCA and logistic regression models in this analysis can help me predict whether it will rain the next day. In the prediction, the model can provide the probability of raining the next day, and the accuracy of the prediction is up to 89.41% (2PCs).

2: Taken together, the 2PCs model and the 3PCs model have no significant difference in final accuracy, which is the same as our Scree Plot. However, the construction of PCA can significantly improve the accuracy of the model in predicting whether it will rain or not on the next day. From the F1 Score, the values of 2PC and 3PC are around 0.895, while the value of no PC is 0.826. In this analysis, the construction of PCA can improve the accuracy of the model by 8.35%.

3: Through the final accuracy comparison, the three models are not as good as the Recal on Precision. If I have more time, I will dig deeper into the data, find out the reasons and improve their Precision.
